WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.360
Thanks for joining my talk today. I hope you guys brought along your shovels since we're

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:13.960
going to be talking about digging a pit of success. Over the next 15 minutes or so, I'm

00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:19.280
going to talk about a framework that we developed at our organization for developing a pit of

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:26.360
success. And so let me talk a little bit about me before I dive into that.

00:00:26.360 --> 00:00:32.480
My name is Aaron Chafetz. I work for a federal agency called USAID as an economist, and I

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:38.939
work in the Office of HIV AIDS. Our work in the Office of HIV AIDS feeds into a larger

00:00:38.939 --> 00:00:44.759
interagency effort known as PEPFAR, the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief. PEPFAR was

00:00:44.759 --> 00:00:52.040
started in 2004 with the goal of ending the global HIV epidemic. And we work in interagency

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:59.520
fashion with a host of other agencies like CDC, Department of Defense, and Peace Corps.

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:05.360
So one of the success factors, one of the factors that has made PEPFAR so successful

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:11.879
is the reliance and the push to collect measurement and evaluation data across the world. So what

00:01:11.879 --> 00:01:16.839
does that data look like? We're collecting data on HIV status, treatment status, and

00:01:16.839 --> 00:01:24.040
prevention indicators, upwards of maybe 30 different indicators collected at 30,000 health

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:30.440
facilities all across the globe. This data also is coming in each quarter to us. So as

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:36.519
you can imagine, this adds up very quickly, and we are swimming in data. What makes this

00:01:36.519 --> 00:01:41.739
even more challenging is when you don't have the right tools for the job. So when I started

00:01:41.739 --> 00:01:49.459
in the Office of HIV-AIDS back in 2015, the primary means of doing analysis was Excel.

00:01:49.459 --> 00:01:56.540
Excel is great, and there's, you know, clearly there are useful uses for it. But when you're

00:01:56.540 --> 00:02:01.860
working with data that come in so frequently and are so large, it's probably not the right

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:07.820
tool for the job. And at that point, you kind of have to recognize that there are better

00:02:07.820 --> 00:02:13.699
things out there, much like R. And so that's when I started in 2016, started realizing

00:02:13.699 --> 00:02:19.740
that there was a use case here for using R. I had been using Stata as an economist, but

00:02:19.740 --> 00:02:24.139
even Stata, Stats package, didn't quite cut it in terms of the scale of the data we were

00:02:24.139 --> 00:02:31.940
working with. And I got really excited about R and really spent a long time learning this

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:37.779
and tried then to convince other people in our organization that R was a great path forward

00:02:37.779 --> 00:02:44.339
and we needed to learn it. Problem, though, you know, R has a steep learning curve, and

00:02:44.339 --> 00:02:49.500
so trying to convince other people to learn R is much like telling them just go out and

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:54.660
run a marathon, right? It's not easy to do, especially when you don't have a training

00:02:54.660 --> 00:03:01.820
plan in place. And so after a few unsuccessful years of proselytizing R, just talking about

00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:07.660
it, what I realized our organization needed was a pit of success. We needed something

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:14.580
that users didn't have to go it alone when they were learning new skill like R.

00:03:14.580 --> 00:03:19.899
The problem, I think, in terms of this idea of success is we often frame it as one of

00:03:19.899 --> 00:03:25.300
climbing a mountain, right? We have to fight this uphill battle, and only when we have

00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:31.100
summited this mountain after all of this work, we have achieved something. The idea, though,

00:03:31.100 --> 00:03:37.460
a pit of success is flipping that on its head. It's saying why can't we create an infrastructure

00:03:37.460 --> 00:03:44.539
so that in order to succeed, it's as easy as falling into that pit? And in order to

00:03:44.539 --> 00:03:49.300
do so, we kind of lay out the guide rails and the framework to make this easy for other

00:03:49.300 --> 00:03:55.539
people to do. This is by no means a new concept or one that

00:03:55.539 --> 00:04:02.539
I came up with. Hadley was talking about it way back in 2016 in relation to the tidyverse.

00:04:02.539 --> 00:04:07.779
And the tidyverse definitely was the primary pit of success for me in learning R, and I

00:04:07.779 --> 00:04:15.259
think this framework also applies to an organization. Problem is, if Hadley's talking about it,

00:04:15.259 --> 00:04:19.500
why aren't we all already doing this already? And I think there are definitely some clear

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:25.859
barriers in the way of doing this. Obviously, it's resource intensive to set up this pit.

00:04:25.859 --> 00:04:32.339
You need people to kind of shine that light to show others the path to move this forward.

00:04:32.339 --> 00:04:36.299
And it's time intensive, both for those people who are leading the way and for new people

00:04:36.299 --> 00:04:41.500
to come on and learn the skill. And then lastly, as part of the government,

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:45.859
our hiring practices are just definitely not as nimble as the private sector, and our data

00:04:45.859 --> 00:04:52.899
stacks are a little slower to innovate. So I want to talk about three ways in which

00:04:52.899 --> 00:04:58.420
we were able to dig this pit of success at our organization. The first, the primary means

00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:03.799
of doing so was developing packages to create that infrastructure, then creating buy-in

00:05:03.799 --> 00:05:10.260
at multiple levels, and then lastly, fostering community of support for our users.

00:05:10.260 --> 00:05:17.299
So starting things off, I think the foundations of this pit of success were through packages.

00:05:17.299 --> 00:05:22.700
Our work in PEPFAR, we, as I mentioned earlier, have lots and lots of data, measurement and

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:27.579
valuation data, that's coming in every quarter. And this is a good means to automate something,

00:05:27.579 --> 00:05:32.739
and R is a great tool for that. So if we have this data that's similar and coming in, we

00:05:32.739 --> 00:05:37.739
can start writing scripts that we can automate. Oh, and those scripts, as we get more comfortable,

00:05:37.739 --> 00:05:42.100
we can turn into functions. So that those functions are useful to you, but they're also

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:48.940
can be useful to others. And slowly, started developing packages. Initially by myself,

00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:55.500
but I saw that this is a means to help others enter the field and learn R. So as I became

00:05:55.500 --> 00:06:00.059
more proficient in R, and we started bringing on more people who learned R, and we had more

00:06:00.059 --> 00:06:04.739
expertise there, we were able to grow out this infrastructure to allow new people to

00:06:04.739 --> 00:06:10.380
enter more easily. So we've developed over time a ton of different packages, whether

00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:15.500
they are around solving a problem for a particular project that we have to repeat, or they're

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:19.980
more general utility functions so that people don't have to recreate the wheel every time

00:06:19.980 --> 00:06:25.100
they encounter a problem. So an example of this is one of our utility packages called

00:06:25.100 --> 00:06:29.540
Glamour, where we do something as simple as setting up a folder structure, right? Doing

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:33.700
this manually is very easy to do, but when you're talking about having to repeat this

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:39.019
process across lots and lots of different projects and doing this across lots of users,

00:06:39.019 --> 00:06:43.500
having something that allows you to just fall into that pit of success is important. And

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:48.500
we do this through a lot of different ways. So like loading secrets, securely storing

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:53.339
and loading secrets to make it easy for people to have all their credentials in one place

00:06:53.339 --> 00:06:59.980
and to make sure that they're not posting this to GitHub and posting their credentials.

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:05.779
So packages really founded the foundation of this infrastructure, because they created

00:07:05.779 --> 00:07:13.380
reproducibility for our work and consistency across all of our users. And more importantly,

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:18.059
this created an approachable way for new users to come on without having to know the full

00:07:18.059 --> 00:07:23.100
R ecosystem, but they had tools that were specific to our workflows that they could

00:07:23.100 --> 00:07:30.179
use and take advantage of. So while we had those packages, we didn't really have the

00:07:30.179 --> 00:07:35.779
buy-in. We didn't have people clamoring to be at the table to use R. And where we started

00:07:35.779 --> 00:07:41.459
to be able to turn things around was really convincing leadership that R was the right

00:07:41.459 --> 00:07:47.859
direction to go. Leadership is really critical, because they're the ones who are ultimately

00:07:47.859 --> 00:07:52.420
creating that tradeoff structure, telling analysts whether they should be focusing their

00:07:52.420 --> 00:07:57.299
attention on training versus having to turn around products, right? Because there's always

00:07:57.299 --> 00:08:04.260
that need for those concrete products. So that they can create that influence both in

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:09.059
the workforce and as they're hiring new staff on, can see this as a marker when they're

00:08:09.059 --> 00:08:16.500
looking at CVs in order to bring that on. And the way we were able to lure in our leadership

00:08:16.619 --> 00:08:22.619
was through concrete products. We were able to, and specifically around visualizations.

00:08:22.619 --> 00:08:27.339
We were able to build off GG plot by creating our own package glitter that used our own

00:08:27.339 --> 00:08:33.659
themes and colors that allowed us to quickly and efficiently create high-quality products

00:08:33.659 --> 00:08:38.900
that our leadership could use to understand where our progress was at and use these as

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:45.340
communication pieces. And they wanted to see more and more of these more quickly. We also

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:51.500
had to convince our colleagues that R is a worthwhile investment, right? And so I think

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:55.900
it's clear automation makes a ton of sense to all of us in this room, but there is that

00:08:55.900 --> 00:09:01.299
learning curve. And so we needed to convince our colleagues that that upfront investment

00:09:01.299 --> 00:09:07.780
cost is worthwhile. Spending anywhere from two hours to two weeks to invest that process

00:09:07.780 --> 00:09:12.580
so then in a year, when you're rerunning all of these things, it only takes seconds to

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:18.539
run those analyses, as opposed to having to do that comfort in a point-and-click world

00:09:18.539 --> 00:09:24.739
where, yes, it's easy to do, that you have spent 40 minutes on it instead of two weeks,

00:09:24.739 --> 00:09:29.380
but you have to spend that 40 minutes every single time that you're doing this. And so

00:09:29.380 --> 00:09:35.780
the way we were able to influence change for our colleagues was to curate support to their

00:09:35.780 --> 00:09:41.500
different workflows and intervene in specific instances. So maybe it was working with a

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:46.380
colleague to show them how to set up and work with them to support an API to bring their

00:09:46.380 --> 00:09:51.619
data in without having to do a manual download of data. Or maybe it was showing them how

00:09:51.619 --> 00:09:58.619
to create calculations before they moved their data into Tableau. Or maybe they felt comfortable

00:09:58.619 --> 00:10:02.619
in the point-and-click world for all of their munging, but then wanted to have a high-quality

00:10:02.619 --> 00:10:08.940
product using R for the visualization side. So it's great. We started to have some buy-in

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:13.979
from our users, but we needed then this last piece of community. We needed to support them

00:10:13.979 --> 00:10:18.940
in some way. And I think everybody here is familiar, as you've started R or some new

00:10:18.940 --> 00:10:23.260
programming language, there's lots of resources out there, and it's easy to be inundated and

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:28.539
overwhelmed by everything and not sure where you should start learning. And so we realized

00:10:28.539 --> 00:10:34.700
early on that we needed to curate an approach for them, a path that they could move forward

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:39.659
so that they knew what direction to go and what was applicable for our work.

00:10:39.659 --> 00:10:43.820
So as a result, we created a community of practice in our office called Core, which

00:10:43.820 --> 00:10:48.659
is really founded on the ideas of being able to share our workflows and best practices

00:10:48.659 --> 00:10:54.979
between inexperienced users and the ones who had a lot more experience. And as we developed

00:10:54.979 --> 00:11:00.059
more and more R users, we could do things like having one-on-one mentorship that we

00:11:00.059 --> 00:11:04.780
had people who had been around and knew what was going on. We were able to develop classroom-like

00:11:04.780 --> 00:11:12.299
settings to have more people able to kind of know the one-on-ones of R. Setting up a

00:11:12.299 --> 00:11:16.299
Slack channel was really important as well, because it created a forum that people could

00:11:16.299 --> 00:11:21.460
feel like they could ask questions very easily, and other people could share new things that

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:26.140
they'd learned. And it didn't have to be a one-way street like a classroom setting.

00:11:26.140 --> 00:11:31.059
And then lastly, just kind of setting up infrequent makeover challenges so people became

00:11:31.059 --> 00:11:36.479
more familiar with ggplot. So here's kind of an example of how we tailored our approach

00:11:36.479 --> 00:11:43.900
in the classroom setting. So myself and other colleagues set up a 12-part series that's

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:48.780
based on R for Data Science. The core principles from R for Data Science are there, and many

00:11:48.780 --> 00:11:53.299
of these chapters are almost copied verbatim. But the difference, though, is we tailored

00:11:53.299 --> 00:11:59.580
the data to what our analysts were familiar with. We used our PEPFAR data so that an analyst

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:05.099
understood the funda—could focus on the fundamentals of R rather than having to worry

00:12:05.099 --> 00:12:11.619
about new data. We also tailored all of the examples to things that worked in our workflow,

00:12:11.619 --> 00:12:15.820
so that they understood the data, they understood these workflows, and could go from the classroom-like

00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:21.919
setting to apply it the very next day in their work, which was quite successful.

00:12:21.919 --> 00:12:26.559
So setting up this pit of success was something that just didn't happen overnight and did

00:12:26.559 --> 00:12:32.080
take a lot of time, and it's something that we have still been continuing to do. And over

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:37.640
the last few years, we have drastically—we've drastically increased our user base. But I

00:12:37.640 --> 00:12:41.440
think what's important is not just the number of users we have but the work we've been able

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:47.039
to produce. We've been able to increase our efficiency and do more and higher-quality

00:12:47.039 --> 00:12:51.760
work as a result of more of an emphasis in R.

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:56.719
I think this model of kind of building a success and creating an infrastructure for others

00:12:56.719 --> 00:13:01.919
in your organization is really important, and I'm happy to be a resource for anybody

00:13:01.919 --> 00:13:06.559
who's trying—feels like you are that N of one at your organization and wanting to set

00:13:06.559 --> 00:13:11.719
this up. My email here, and it's in the next slide as well. And then I have some additional

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:17.559
resources that are posted on this slide and are also on the conference website as well.

00:13:17.559 --> 00:13:22.840
So with that, I'll end, and I wish any of you who are willing to take on this challenge

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:29.840
the best of luck in digging a pit of success for your organization.

